						<a href="http://www.nutsvolts.com/magazine/article/the-ac-volt"><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.nutsvolts.com/uploads/articles/NV_0497_Tipton_thumb.jpg" alt="The AC Volt" /></a>
					</div>
					<div class="col-md-5">
						<h6 class="tags">Theory</h6>
						<h2><a href="http://www.nutsvolts.com/magazine/article/the-ac-volt" style="color:#333">The AC Volt</a></h2>
						<p><p>In the US, the DC volt is legally defined by the Josephson array &mdash; a super conducting quantum device with a highly repeatable output voltage. Banks of standard cells and temperature-stabilized zener diode references are used by the National Institute of Science and Technology (NIST) to calibrate DC meters for scientific and industrial customers. So how is the AC volt defined?</p></p>
					</div>
					
				</div>
				
				
				
				<hr />
			
				<div class="row">
					
					<div class="col-md-7">
						<a href="http://www.nutsvolts.com/magazine/article/august2013_Bates"><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.nutsvolts.com/uploads/articles/NV_0813_Bates_Thumb.jpg" alt="Build Your Own Induction Charger" /></a>
					</div>
					<div class="col-md-5">
						<h6 class="tags">Wireless</h6>
						<h2><a href="http://www.nutsvolts.com/magazine/article/august2013_Bates" style="color:#333">Build Your Own Induction Charger</a></h2>
						<p><p>As an avid hobbyist, I wanted a convenient way to recharge my battery powered projects without having to tie up the USB ports on my computer. Borrowing from the concept of the wireless chargers on the market, I decided to build my own. So if you like the idea of having a wireless replacement for your USB port, open up your surplus parts drawer and let&#39;s start the induction process.</p></p>
					</div>
					
				</div>
				
				
				
